Containers vs Virtual Machines
Explain differences in:
Architecture
Resource usage
Boot time
Isolation level
Kernel usage

Solution:-
🔹 Architecture
Virtual Machine:
Hardware
→ Hypervisor
→ Guest OS
→ Binaries/Libraries
→ App

Each VM:

Has its own kernel

Has its own full OS

Container:
Hardware
→ Host OS
→ Host Kernel
→ Docker Daemon
→ Container (isolated process)

Containers:

Share host kernel

Use namespaces + cgroups

No separate OS

🔹 Resource Usage

VM:

Full OS memory footprint

Kernel memory

Virtual hardware

Heavy storage

Container:

Just processes

Shared kernel

Much smaller memory footprint

🔹 Boot Time

VM:

Boots entire OS (minutes)

Container:

Starts process (milliseconds)

🔹 Isolation Level

VM:

Hardware-level isolation

Strong security boundary

Container:

Process-level isolation

Shared kernel

Weaker boundary

🔹 Kernel Usage

VM:

Each VM has its own kernel

Container:

All containers share host kernel

This is critical.
